We would have never thought we would sit and talk all the way till the sunset. Idly strolling down the lonely street with incomplete feet was interesting too. We finally reached the main property where the dirty, smelly, blue & small (I called them artisanan) train waits from Santa Cruz. Me and another friend boarded the train. Inside was just me, him and no Indians. We both sat idly in the train and had our dinner on the way. Apparently, none of you could think about feeling dizzy on the train. Given the fact, todays generation drive faster car than before. There is a possibility of few people in India have headaches while driving. The trains in South America moves in a real slow pace which hardly takes any kind of motion sickness (from my experience).

Incidentally, we liked the service because, it comes on time. The engine begins its play with going fast and slower over days. We bowed our heads to catch the train ride before sunrise. We rushed to find a place to sit because we did’nt knew when the rush will start. All of us sat patiently and tried to cross board the train. We got down once we were comfortable enough to sit.
